  "opinion": "As a man in his late fifties who spent most of his life in Bologna without formal higher education beyond lower secondary, I've seen firsthand how stereotypes about STEM fields can silently undermine people's confidence. Growing up in a family where one parent had a bachelor's degree but the other had no formal education, I understand the complex dynamics of expectations and limitations. Stereotype threat isn't just an academic concept—it's the feeling that your intelligence or abilities might be judged negatively because of who you are. For instance, when I saw my son, who's in high school, hesitate to take a physics class because he's been told girls are 'not good at math,' I realized how deeply these beliefs can affect even the next generation. The problem isn't just in classrooms; it's in the very culture of STEM fields where people feel they don't belong. Given my depression and the way I've spent hours daily on social media, I've noticed how these stereotypes can make people feel isolated and anxious. Addressing stereotype threat requires more than just awareness—it needs practical, community-based solutions. We should create safe spaces where people can explore STEM without fear of judgment, like local workshops or mentorship programs that focus on real-world applications rather than theoretical challenges. This is especially important for those from backgrounds where formal education isn't the norm. It's not about changing the system overnight but building trust and support step by step. In my experience, the most effective approach is to start small—maybe with a neighborhood initiative that connects local high school students with professionals who can show them how STEM can be both accessible and exciting.",
